Current 7-day av. is 33.69k /day. I'm expecting the current trend to be affected by the recent opening up of restrictions and gradually increasing transmission creating a gradual slowing of the current decline in cases, with a realistic minimum of cases dropping to circa 10k and averaging ~ 21k/day. Max would be the current decline tapering off within two weeks to a plateau, averaging ~27k/day.

3.93 million today. 370,000 more confirmed cases would get us into Bin C. 25 days remaining. Need to see 14,800 new cases per day average to cross that threshold. Rolling 7-day average is currently 34,755, and dropping by about 2.87% cases per day. Assuming constant rates (nothing is constant!!), something like 600,000 new cases might be expected by end of month.

Revised forecast as cumulative cases have reached 3.89 million, exceeding the number in the lowest bucket. Assigned equal probability to scenarios that cumulative cases fall between 3.8 million-4.3 million and 4.3 million-4.8 million as 4.3 million represents approximately 102k weekly cases over the remainder of July, which seems a reasonable approximation given current rate of weekly decline in confirmed cases. Continued decline in cases appears likely given Taiwan's 88% vaccination rate along with growing incidence of positive cases. Maintaining some probability of re-acceleration which could be caused by Omicron variant continuing to break through or identification of a new variant.

As of 1 July, according to Our World In Data, there are 3.8 million cases, so this is the floor. Further, there are 40,000 cases per day over the last 7-days, so assuming a flat trajectory, we have a forecast of 5,000,000 = 3.8 million + 40,000 * 30.

They seem to be loosening up, but I don't have anything that shifts my credence much either way.Their reproduction for the last few days has been low but I place about 40% probability it stays below 1, so my prediction is weighted up a bit.

Cumulative cases as of 19 June were 3.73 million with 7-day rolling average cases declining at an accelerated rate, down from to 44k from a peak around 80k one month ago. Projecting most likely outcome around 4.1 million cases based on estimate of continued weekly reduction in cases over July at 200k, 100k, 50k, and 25k for the final partial week. In order for cumulative cases to total less than 3.8 million, weekly cases over the month of July would have to average 56k, marking a precipitous drop from current levels, not consistent with case waves observed in other countries. Likewise, in order for cumulative cases to total more than 5.3 million, weekly cases over the month of July would have to re-accelerate to an average of 330k, also inconsistent with case waves observed globally. This projection estimates a 70% probability that case rates continue to fall at a steady pattern over the month of July, resulting in cumulative cases between 3.8-4.8 million.
Taking current month on month run rate as current trajectory, giving additional weighting to bucket below to account for deceleration

Vs World, Asia, US, India. SK, Russia, JP, Malaysia, Taiwan visual, in log. Positivity for countries range from 7.5-30% of population, assume 30% positivity gets to >6.3mm. Doesn't seem to correlate with vaccination rate, it's been ~90% for months before the outbreak.

Currently, there has been a total of 3.64 Million with a 7 day rolling average of 44k/day which is half of what it was a month ago. With a month to go that would add up to another 1.3 million cases were things to be linear, which they never are. So I think bin 4 and above are out unless there is some very new set of circumstances. Bin 1 also seems to be optimistic as even an average of 600 cases would get them over that line but it's still a remote possibility. On the other hand, bin 3 doesn't take into account the rapid fall in cases.
